26:58.940 --> 27:05.780
So it's protecting data in use using hardware-based, attested trust execution environment.

27:05.780 --> 27:10.460
Lots of words, and I'm going to try briefly to explain what some of them mean.

27:10.460 --> 27:14.260
So normal protection of data, right?

27:14.260 --> 27:17.100
You can stop workloads messing with each other.

27:17.100 --> 27:19.340
Containers messing with each other, VMs messing with each other.

27:19.340 --> 27:20.540
That's fine, we know how to do that.

27:20.540 --> 27:21.540
That's not so difficult.

27:21.540 --> 27:22.540
Type one.

27:22.540 --> 27:23.540
Type two.

27:23.540 --> 27:27.180
That's stopping your workload from messing with your host.

27:27.180 --> 27:28.180
That's a bad thing.

27:28.180 --> 27:29.180
We know how to do that.

27:29.180 --> 27:33.980
But it's much, much more difficult to do this last type.

27:33.980 --> 27:38.580
Stopping your host messing with your workload, right?

27:38.580 --> 27:43.980
Because of how memory pages work and virtualization and all those sorts of things in containers.

27:43.980 --> 27:50.260
And so confidential computing is about using hardware-based, chip-based CPU, GPU capabilities

27:50.260 --> 27:52.540
to enforce that.

27:52.540 --> 27:56.540
It's one of a bunch of things called PETs, Privacy Enhancing Technologies.

27:56.540 --> 27:59.060
You've probably heard of things like fully homomorphic encryption.

27:59.060 --> 28:01.820
